# Station Tycoon v3 — Phase 1

Deterministic, server-recomputable simulation engine + refactored game front end.
This is the foundation for the monthly leaderboard challenge: every score can be
reproduced bit-for-bit from `(config, scenarioId)`, so the server never has to
trust a client-submitted number.

## Files

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `engine.js` | Pure sim engine. UMD module: `window.StationEngine` in the browser, `require('./engine')` in Node. No DOM, no `Math.random()`. |
| `scenarios.js` | Monthly scenario definitions (site, tariff, grid limit, # demand days). Treat published entries as immutable. |
| `index.html` | The game, wired to the engine. Day 1 is animated; the official score averages 7 seeded demand days and renders on completion. |
| `test.js` | Verification suite: `node test.js` |

## How scoring works

- Each scenario defines 7 demand days. Day `d` uses a PRNG seeded from
  `hash(scenario.id + '::day' + d)`, so demand traces are fixed for the month
  and identical for every player.
- **Score = avg daily profit × (avg happiness)²** when profitable; raw average
  profit when not. Happiness = % of drivers averaging ≥90% of requested power
  (balked and reneged drivers count as unhappy).
- The animated day the player watches is demand day 0 of the scoring set —
  what you watch is what you're scored on (1/7th of it, anyway).

## Phase 2 integration contract

The client submits **only** `{ scenarioId, config }` where config is
`{ ports, portKW, drawLimit, battery, price }`. The serverless endpoint:

```js
const E = require('./engine');
const Scenarios = require('./scenarios');
const scn = Scenarios.get(body.scenarioId);          // reject unknown/closed months
const result = E.scoreConfig(body.config, scn);      // validateConfig runs inside
// result.score is authoritative; ignore anything the client claims
```

Pin `engine.js` + `scenarios.js` to identical versions on client and server
(the score payload includes `engineVersion` for sanity checking). Any change to
engine constants mid-month invalidates the month's leaderboard — version-gate
deployments accordingly.

## Verified (test.js)

- Determinism: identical config → identical 7-day results and score.
- Parity: a manually ticked animated day exactly equals the batch `runDay`.
- Validation: out-of-range configs clamp; non-numeric configs throw.
- Sanity sweep: no NaN across a config grid; scores order plausibly.

## Balance (v3.1.0, verified by 2,100-config sweep)

The v3.0.0 exploit — pin price at the slider max — is closed. Price elasticity
was strengthened (exponent 0.8 → 1.4, demand clamp widened to [0.3, 2.0]),
making the revenue-optimal price interior (~$0.50–0.55 on the June scenario)
with score falling off in both directions.

Resulting meta on scenario 2026-06, sweeping ports × portKW × drawLimit ×
battery × price (2,100 configs):

- Winner: 6 ports / 350 kW / draw limit 500 of 600 / battery / $0.50.
- All of the top 20 configs use the battery; 14 of 20 cap draw below the
  interconnection.
- The best battery-free design ranks #99, scoring ~12% below the winner —
  the battery is decisive but not an auto-win; sizing still matters.
- Overbuilds (10–12 ports, 400 kW) no longer appear in the top ranks.

Re-tune per scenario by adjusting tariff values in `scenarios.js` (higher
demand charges push optimal draw limits lower). Engine constants are frozen
for any month with posted scores; bump VERSION on any change.
